Hey everyone! As a private chef, there’s nothing I love more than bringing people together over a delicious meal. Recently, I had the pleasure of catering a family-style dinner party and it was an absolute blast!

Seeing everyone gathered around the table, passing dishes and sharing stories, was truly heartwarming. And the food? Well, let’s just say there were a lot of happy stomachs that night!

Being a creative in the culinary industry, I’m passionate about using experimenting and being progressve when it comes to the influence in my menus but my culinary approach is a bit classic with a little razzle dazzle. And it works out for me because  most times  my clients like a more traditional approach too with a little spark. 🫶🏽It’s not just about the food, but also about the experience and the connections we make with one another. The ability to turn up or down is clutch because I like to give my clients what they want. 🫶🏽

So, my call to action for you all is to gather your loved ones around the table and share a meal together. Whether it’s a fancy dinner party or a casual potluck, it’s the moments we create with each other that truly matter. And of course, if you need a private chef to make it extra special, you know where to find me 😉. #privatecheflife #blackgirlmagic #familydinner #chef #columbuschef #privatechefcolumbus #ohiochef

⏰ Life is short, and if you’ve been daydreaming about starting something, consider this your sign! It’s time to DO THAT ISH!!!!. 🌟

We all start somewhere and it might be confusing at first, but here are some invaluable tips:

1️⃣ GOOGLE is your friend. Its cliche but 🤷🏾‍♀️ many people don’t use google as much as they should. It’s all about WHAT you search. Looking for ‘how to start’, ‘where to find’, ‘top’, ‘startup’, ‘beginner-friendly’... Trust the process and soon you’ll navigate through it like a pro! You have to read countless articles! One ain’t enough. Two isn’t either. 

2. TIKTOK is not just about the dances. It’s a goldmine of knowledge if you know where to look. Use it like a search engine like google! And once you’re ready to dive deeper, YOUTUBE is your next stop for more extensive content.

🔑 🏆OPENAI’s #ChatGPT is another amazing tool to utilize. I use it personally and can attest to its benefits! 

Here’s a beginner’s template: 

“I want to_______..currently, I already have ______ in place. Act as though you are now ______. (specifically role)_______. Your objective is to create a _______(what u want them to do) which involves _______ , build _______ , as well as _______ , specifically for _______(which platform). Please provide your results in a _____ way.”

Stay tuned for more posts with specific examples and more templates! 

📌Turn on notifications so you never miss out. If you’re starting a new journey, let us know in the comments! 

🚀 #TransformationCoach #Motivation #StartNow #LifeIsShort #DoItNow #TipsForSuccess #OpenAI #Google #TikTok #YouTube

1. It’s about to be year 4 for the Build A bond Toy Drive. 🥺(this photo is from year one)

3. That since i started the toy drive, I’ve had so much support from so many people in order to make this possible for so many families. Let let let y’all inside: Last year changed it a bit bc i was able to go inside the jails and actually meet the parents who were apart of the toy drive. I watched them shop for their children. I watched them pick wrapping paper , i watched them wrap the gifts. I watched dads skip over the makeup on the teen tables because “they ain’t goin for that” 😂🫶🏽i watched moms make sure the things she shopped for was even because she didn’t want her kids fighting over a particular item. And it’s a proven fact that when an incarcerated has a RANGE of support it is more likely for them to do better. 🫶🏽

1 in 14 children in Ohio have had an incarcerated parent. We have one of the highest rates of children with an incarcerated parent. 
The incarcerated men and women , their children and families is who I advocate for because it’s personal for me. My passions are passions because it’s personal. I’ve been the incarcerated parent and I’ve also been support for family members who are incarcerated. This fight is real and no a toy won’t change it but having a village and extra support from the community during hard times def helps within the journey. Creating positive connections between the parents and the kids, relieving stress for the single parent or caregivers, providing resources and creating positive memories during a hard time is proven to help with the chances of reoffending. 
I made a choice to be apart of the solution instead of sitting around talking about “what should be happening” and every year, i could not do it with out the community. 🫶🏽 Issa Village.

I rock a purple chef coat – not just for the love of cooking, but for something deeply personal. 

When I was just 9 years old, I witnessed a horrific scene that no child should ever have to see: my mother being brutally attacked by my stepdad. She was stabbed over 25 times. Leaving her paralyzed with major setbacks in life. That dark day left me with a responsibility beyond my tender age: fleeing to safety with my baby brothers. 

I share this not for pity, but to shine a light on the shadows of domestic violence. Many silently suffer, and countless others bear the scars of witnessing such cruelty. If my story  can help even one person find the strength to speak out, seek help, or support a loved one, then wearing this purple coat becomes more than just a fashion statement – it’s a beacon of hope.

This month, as we observe #DomesticViolenceAwarenessMonth, let’s remember the survivors, the witnesses, and those we’ve lost. Let’s raise our voices, and in our own ways, be the change we wish to see.

Rest in heaven to my mom @jeananneboston my favorite warrior 💜💜💜💜💜💜😇

#EndTheSilence #DomesticViolenceAwareness

I’m approaching year 4 following my heart with this toy drive. Every year I have learned so much-making the following year better. I don’t know where I’d be with out my partner in the hood fight @tressy13 . It really takes a village even when trying to do something for the village lol. 🫶🏽🫶🏽

Since this was aired, we made some changes and I no longer shop for the kids because we create stores in the jails for the parents to shop for their kids on their own. That was like a dream to me when i first started this and it was such an impact when i seen the parents shopping for their kids and wrapping the gifts and stuff. I had to hold myself together bc i didn’t wNt them to see me cry but it was truly a full circle. I remember feeling helpless in prison around the holidays sending home stuffed animals that ppl inside made out of crochet. Wasn’t no store for me to shop for my son so i just prayed my family got him right while i was gone and they did… but i was in there with so many different type of females with different circumstances with their kids and their lack of support from family members. This shit is so deep for me because it’s bigger than me… and although you may have not experienced it… just imagine it…… imagine being in prison, then add on at Christmas time away from your kids…. You can’t imagine it…. It’s beyond your imagination….. you can support a lotta ways.  Cash app $buildabondtoydrive and the go fund me and Amazon link is in my bio. 🫶🏽🫶🏽💪🏽

To be able to reach more families, I’m excited to announce we are having a toy pick up for the families. The last 3 years we drove around Columbus for 2 dayshsnd delivering gifts and reading letters. Just me and @tressy13 (last year we were bless to have added to that team 💪🏽🫶🏽) and still was running out of time. There’s only so many houses we can physically go to and impact is always number one for me. 

I’m currently taking donations by the way of Amazon wishlist, go fund me (links in bio) cash app $buildabondtoydrive and also store pick up in Columbus Ohio under janese Boston. 
I’d love to get 50 bikes and coats as well. 
It takes a village.

Appreciation post! 🚨
This toy drive would not be possible without the support of the donors, staff at the jail and community volunteers. 

Creating a store within 2 jails within 3 days is not an easy feat. There’s so much to do: gathering the participants on the inside, communicating with guardians on the outside, unloading, creating makeshift stores, helping shop, deliveries and last bit certainly not least-the wrapping of hundreds of gifts.

From the beginning i knew i had nothing to offer when it came to wrapping presents. Lol😂 I remember pulling up to the jail and @tressy13 coming to the dock getting stuff to wrap and she even did some at home. 🤦🏽‍♀️ 
I also remember putting gifts in gift bags and calling it a day….🥴😭

Now that we are in the jails, participants have the option to wrap their kids gifts themselves, most are like me and prefer assistance lol!

Last year we were blessed to have volunteers from @onedotchurch and @stjohnschurchcolumbus assist us with the first time we set up in the jails! They truly were lifesavers. 🫶🏽🫶🏽

I just want to say thank you from the bottom of my heart to everyone that helps with this because this is bigger than a traditional toy drive bc it includes a wholeeeeeee process to make this work for the participants to be able to shop themselves for their kids. 

I thank you. We thank you. 🫶🏽🫶🏽🫶🏽

Imagine having to leave your newborn child just 29 days after welcoming him into this world.Having to watch him grow up relying on pictures and visits. Now knowing if he goin to remember you….

 This was my reality as Janese Boston, previously known only as 55973 – a detainee under the jurisdiction of the Ohio Department of Rehabilitation. I spent 4 years, 1,371 days, 32,904 hours, and 1,974,240 minutes separated from my baby boy, imprisoned by circumstances, fighting against a tidal wave of self-doubt. The echo of the thoughts “Will he remember me?” “Will he love me?” “Am I worthy to be his mom?” haunted my every waking moment. My soul yearned for a bond with my son, a desire thwarted by my incarceration. 

 During this time, I strived to reform my thoughts and sharpen my parenting skills, eagerly participating in available programs. A seed of gratitude was sown within me, blossoming into the aspiration to reciprocate the support and kindness showered upon me by the resources i had available on the inside, birthing this Toy Drive Initiative.

 This project is more than a mere distribution of toys; it’s a heartfelt mission to mend the strained threads between incarcerated parents and their children. Currently, 2.7 million children in the US live in the painful silence of parental incarceration, battling the associated trauma, shame, and stigmas. They are the forgotten faces of incarceration, seeking solace in shadows. 

 Now in its fourth year, our mission has evolved from me shopping and delivering gifts to establishing a store inside both jails, empowering parents to shop for their children and offering them a semblance of normalcy and connection.

 Join me in this journey of hope and healing. Contribute by donating. Let’s unite to be the rays of hope in these children’s lives, illuminating their paths with love and connection. 

 With Heartfelt Gratitude and Hope, 

 Janese Boston

I can’t front, that shit hard. Especially when everyone in your comfort zone is about the bullshit and on bullshit. It’s hard Asf to disassociate yourself the people and the environments that was there since day 1. It feels unloyal. In the moment it feel as if you being fake to the ppl who you trauma bonded with. The people “who was there” …Until the day you realize that you showing up for yourself more means showing up for other ppl less. You realize that you will always have a level of respect and love for your people but you gotta have it from a distance. You not being disloyal to them, you being loyal to yourself. You prolly call yourself an introvert because you don’t go outside much…nah. You just don’t wanna go outside to the same places that don’t interest you with people who ain’t on the same shit as you at this point in your life.  The shit hard. But so what…. Your life depends on it.

Imagine being a true believer in the idea of ‘walking in your purpose and watching as God aligns you with what you need along the way’. It’s humbling to say the least. 

As I reflect on my journey, I realize how much ‘walking in my purpose’ has been guided by faith, believing that God got me. The support I’ve received has been nothing short of humbling. Being authentic on social media, showing up as my true self, was a path I believe God wanted for me. Helping people in situations that others May Judge them for and having compassion for the roses that want to grow, is growing and have grown from concrete-is a calling for me..and sometimes i don’t know how to accept support bc I’m so busy tryin to be the support. But this toy drive has made me a better person…and the people along the way that i have connected with has been apart of that journey have given me little doses of confidence…

Them doses matter when fighting a fight that most wouldn’t fight. 

It’s like cheering a boxer on. I’m not getting in the ring but ima hype you up from the sidelines.🫶🏽

 @vegas_jones  help has been invaluable in assisting others through my endeavor this year. Not only did we get @puma apparel -he sent shoes to match! Chileeeeeeeee! 🥺🥹🤲🏽♥️

It’s a powerful reminder of how it truly takes a village to make a difference. And I’m beyond thankful for the support…. God is good.
Chef life gave me confidence when i needed it the most. @gooddaycolumbus 🫶🏽

It’s taken me a few days to fully process the past week. 
This past Saturday we handed out the gifts to the children that the their incarcerated personally shopped for. 
As they shopped, wrapped , labeled their children’s gifts, and wrote them letters, I felt God in the space. I felt confirmation that my very intentional goal with this initiative is exactly what I’m supposed to be doing. It’s bigger than any toy or gift. It’s about these kids knowing they are loved and thought about, it’s about helping the caregivers during the holidays, it’s about giving the incarcerated a chance to provide for their families while they are away. 
Little things add up… so ima offer my 2cent every trip 🫶🏽🫶🏽🫶🏽🫶🏽 and ima ask for yours too… bc without the community this would not be possible. #welcometothegoodlife 

#assenincolumbus #ohiolife #columbusohio

I gotta tell y’all a lil story about my friend @hylyte . We didn’t just meet when i moved to Columbus; we actually randomly met a couple years before. It was at a time when he was the voice of Columbus radio and I was figuring out my own path still working in the clubs and going to culinary school. He took off to LA, chasing big dreams, and there I was at his house, crashing on an air mattress, taking pictures on the patio-and feeling like the luckiest person in the world to see my friend in his element-chasing his dreams.

Now, we’re here in the present, and it’sll so crazy how the last 6-7 years has really been lifechanging.. now it like-Hylyte’s a pillar Columbus, and I’ve found my calling as a chef and community advocate. I invited him to volunteer at my toy drive this year in the new jail while the guys shopped. I watched how he used his experience of a dad of two boys to help the guys shop who had sons. Seeing them recognize him and talk to him as soon as they came in was dope. 
I keep telling yall it’s bigger than a toy drive. My biggest goal is for this to be multifaceted with resources and inspiration and HOPE.
This journey has been nothing short of a sight to witness. 🫶🏽

@hylyte i love you my guy💪🏽 and i appreciate you. You inspire me.
